      "A musty or mildew smell in your car is almost never about the air. It's about water — trapped somewhere in the cabin, feeding microbial growth you can smell but usually can't see. The good news is that this is a solvable problem with a clear order of operations, and once you fix the source it tends to stay fixed. The bad news is that spraying an air freshener over it does nothing but buy you a few hours, and we'll explain exactly why below.",
      "This guide walks through the real causes, a step-by-step removal plan that detailers actually use, and then — only once the cabin is genuinely clean — how to keep it smelling fresh long-term. Be honest with yourself about which stage you're at, because skipping the removal step is the single most common reason the smell keeps coming back.",
      "## Why your car smells musty: the real causes",
      "Mildew and musty odors are produced by mold and bacteria, and those need one thing to thrive: moisture. Find the water and you've found the smell. Here are the usual suspects, roughly in order of how often they're the culprit.",
      "### 1. A clogged AC evaporator drain",
      "Your air conditioning pulls humidity out of the cabin air, and that condensation is supposed to drain out through a small tube under the car. When that drain clogs with debris, water pools against the evaporator inside the dashboard — a dark, damp, perfectly air-conditioned home for mildew. The tell: the smell is strongest in the first few seconds after you turn on the AC, blowing straight out of the vents. If you find a damp passenger-side floor with no obvious spill, a backed-up evaporator drain is a prime suspect.",
      "### 2. Wet carpet, floor mats, or upholstery",
      "Water gets into carpet far more easily than it leaves. A rainy day with the windows cracked, a spilled drink, wet gym clothes, snow tracked in on boots, or a damp dog — any of it soaks into the padding under the carpet, which can stay wet for weeks. Press firmly on the carpet with a paper towel; if it comes up damp, you've found at least part of the problem.",
      "### 3. Clogged sunroof or door drains",
