      "**2. Find and fix the moisture source.** This is non-negotiable. Check the floors for dampness, clear the AC evaporator drain (a gentle pass with compressed air or a thin wire usually clears it), flush the sunroof drains, and inspect seals for leaks. If you clean without fixing the source, the smell returns within days — guaranteed.",
      "**3. Deep-clean the soft surfaces.** Once everything is dry, vacuum thoroughly, then shampoo the carpet and upholstery with a dedicated automotive cleaner and let it dry fully with the windows down. For lingering odor, sprinkle plain baking soda generously over dry carpet and seats, leave it overnight (or up to 24 hours), and vacuum it out — it's a genuinely effective, residue-free odor absorber.",
      "**4. Replace the cabin air filter.** It's inexpensive, usually behind the glovebox, and frequently a five-minute job. A fresh filter removes a hidden odor reservoir and improves airflow at the same time.",
